[***Problem 11. Reflect: Prompt: Is there a difference in the amount a customer is willing to pay and if the stay is a weekend or non-weekend?***]{style="color:royalblue;"}

**Reflect:**

Yes, there is a difference between what city hotel guests are willing to pay for weekend and non-weekend stays. I used the group by and summarize functions built into R to give us a mean of the average daily rate paid by guests whose stays did and did not include a weekend, respectively. Again, we can see that the former, those who did stay over a weekend, paid an average of \$107.60 while those who did not paid an average of \$104.53. While a T-test and comparison against a preset P-value would be needed to determine statistical significance, I can weigh in on practical significance. For me as a college student with limited income and funds, this is a significant difference that could add up over the course of a multi-day stay. However, for someone that is traveling for business and has a company that is paying for their travel, this difference might not even be noticed, let alone considered.

I also ran calculations on the standard deviations of each, or how far on average each value is from the mean. I wasn't surprised to see that there was greater digression from the mean during the week compared to the weekend, as the higher rates of the weekend were likely more closely controlled and monitored by hotel management, whereas the higher supply of available rooms at city hotels during the week likely opened the possibility of offering discounts and incentives to fill these rooms during the week.

